    I recently purchased the small 2.1L Cosori (on sale) for the travel trailer, and after playing with it at home for a week, I decided to get a large AF for the house.  I started with a used Instant 6.7qt from warehouse deals, but ended up returning it immediately.  A couple of issues with it due to it being used, but one thing I noticed was that it felt a bit "flimsy" especially considering the size.  This one arrived the same day (originally intended as a Christmas gift) so I decided to open it up and give it a go.First thing I noticed is that it was definitely more substantial than the Instant AF.  Heavier and the basket is sturdier.  Basket is plenty large for two or 3 people (I'm solo but it's nice to have the volume and 9" width of the basket for more even cooking).The fact that the fan speeds adjust to the type of cooking you are doing is a real improvement.  Most AFs just adjust the temperature and time.  With a difference in fan speeds, the results are more fine-tuned, so to speak.  I had considered getting the Cosori Dual Blaze with the lower element (in addition to the upper) but having seen a number of reviews showing the results not hugely different than a single upper element, I opted for this.  The reviews for this are basically 5 stars across the board, and the varying fan speed is an upgrade, IMHO.My first meal of pork chop, baby potatoes and baby carrots was very tasty!  I was able to do it all in one go, by starting with the potatoes, then adding carrots, then the chop.  The temps were close enough that everything worked out pretty well.  It will take a bit of experimenting to get my results down to where I want them, but for a first go, I would say it was a successful trial run!Note that you can't change the fan speeds independently.  They adjust with the selection of cooking mode, but since you can manually change your temps and time, that is essentially the same thing.  Pick the mode that gives you the fan speed you want, then adjust your temp/time accordingly.There is no "shake" reminder, but I found that my little spuds browned up nicely on the bottom anyway, even without shaking.  If you really feel you need the reminder to shake your contents, just set your initial time to half of the total, and then go and shake it then, and restart at half the time.I'm purchasing another for the gift (which I stole!) while the Black Friday sales are still on and have no hesitation recommending this to anyone.

